I've always been delighted by opposite categories.  Sometimes I think=0A=
we live in one.  For example: if you flip forward in a book you=0A=
eventually reach the back, but if you go back far enough you reach=0A=
the foreword... and in the ancient past everything was younger.=0A=
=0A=
I always tell my students that since category theory reduces all of=0A=
mathematics=0A=
to the study of arrows, and the only mistake you can make with an arrow is=
=0A=
to get confused about which way it's pointing, they should expect to spend=
=0A=
many hours confused about exactly this.=0A=
